LUCK Delivers Solid 4Q expands Brand and Growth Platform

4Q results beat expectations on both revenue and EBITDA, with Season Pass momentum and strategic acquisitions strengthening LUCK's growth platform. Mgmt continues to progress on conversions and expanding the more premium Lucky Strike brand to 100 locations by year-end. Despite softer margin guidance, trends are steadily improving and we see further upside from here.With shares near lows and a robust M&A backdrop, risk/reward looks attractive.

**(1) Top- and Bottom-Line Beat.** LUCK delivered a solid 4Q with revenue of $301.2M (vs cons $294.6M) and adj. EBITDA of $88.7M ($vs cons $84.9M). The beat was driven by targeted marketing and employee engagement initiatives that boosted sales. Effective cost mgmt led to SG&A leverage,with the SG&A rate improving over 200bps YoY to 10.9% (vs cons at 12.2%).

**(2) Season Pass Driving Engagement and F&B Momentum.** LUCK sold over 260k Summer Season Pass (up from 190k last year), generating $13.4M in sales and boosting guest visits and retail spend. LUCK is also executing on plan to grow F&B, with food comps were +2.5% driven by strong innovation. Alcohol comps, while down 2.7%, showed improving trends.

**(3) Strategic Acquisitions and Conversions.** LUCK added five new properties that collectively welcome 1.5M annual guests. These properties were purchased at a fraction of its replacement cost, underscoring their strong capital allocation in high-quality, hard-to-replicate assets. Mgmt plans to expand Lucky Strike from 55 to 100 locations and retiring the Bowlero brand by year-end,consolidating its portfolio under a more premium brand.

**(1) Light Guidance.** FY26 sales guidance of $1.26B-$1.31B (+5-9%) and adj. EBITDA of $375M-$415M came in-line with cons. However, EBITDA margins were softer at ~30.7% at the midpoint.Mgmt cited a 12-18 month acquisition integration timeline as a near-term margin headwind.

**(2) Comp Still Negative But Improving.** Same-store revenue declined 4.1% YoY in 4Q (vs. -5.6% in 3Q), reflecting primarily&slower recovery in corporate events. However, management noted steady monthly improvement with trends remaining positive from May to August, driven by strong uptake of the Summer Season Pass program.

LUCK enters FY26 with momentum from acquisitions, organic initiatives, and improving comps.With shares near historical lows and a favorable M&A backdrop, we see asymmetric risk/reward and a&ceterate our Buy rating.

We believe Lucky Strike's strong brand, large and growing center footprint, and leading entertainment experience are likely to further bolster its competitive positioning in the large and highly fragmented bowling industry.
Risk/Reward - 12 Month View

- Continued industry growth and ongoing consolidation by Lucky Strike.- Ongoing unit growth through M&A and greenfield activities.- Margin expansion through ongoing improvements to existing centers, efficiencies gained through QMS, and greater customer engagement through gamification driving fixed cost leverage.- \(\) 18\(PT, based on F27E EBITDA of\) \ \(420M\) , \(\sim 11x\) EV/EBITDA.

- Consumer interest in bowling increases faster than expected, driving upside to sales.- Gamification through app generates stronger engagement and frequency than expected, driving sales higher.- Unit expansion is more robust than modeled.- QMS drives greater efficiency improvements than anticipated.- Greater fixed cost leverage on higher sales.- \(\) 28\(Upside PT, based on F27E EBITDA of\) \ \(429M\) , \(\sim 14x\) EV/EBITDA.

- Higher wage expense pressures EBITDA margin expansion.- M&A valuation multiples increase meaningfully and greenfield economics are worse than anticipated.- Fixed cost leverage is lower than expected.- \(\) 5\(Downside PT, based on F27E EBITDA of\) \ \(332M\) , \(\sim 6x\) EV/EBITDA.

Top material issue(s): 1) Energy Usage. As the largest operator of bowling centers (by number of locations) in the world, we believe LUCK is focused on sustainability and managing its energy usage more efficiently.

Company Target(s): 1) Key initiatives include the installation of solar panels on bowling center roofs, installation of LED lighting fixtures, installation of Energy Management Systems, and reducing the use of disposables in increasing the use of reusable.

Qs to mgmt: 1) What are your primary focuses from an ESG perspective? 2) What additional efforts can you take to reduce energy usage? 3) How does your energy usage compare to other bowling center operators in the industry? 4) Is there a noticeable improvement in energy efficiency from center remedies? 5) How are you addressing DE&I within your employee ranks? 6) What do you think your customers and employees care most about from an ESG perspective and how are you responding to that?
ESG Sector Deep Dive: Multiline and Specialty Retailers & Distributors
- New "greenfield" center openings- Additional center acquisitions- International expansion

Lucky StrikeLucky Strike is the largest operator of bowling entertainment centers in the US and globally, with more than 320 locations across multiple banners. The company operates traditional bowling centers and more upscale entertainment concepts with lounge seating, arcades, enhanced food and beverage offerings, and more robust customer service for individuals and group events, as well as hosting and overseeing professional and nonprofessional bowling tournaments and related broadcasting.

Our \(\) 18\$ price target is based on \(\sim 11x\) F26E EV/EBITDA. Risks include expense inflation, particularly wages, macro risks, and inability to acquire new locations at attractive valuation multiples.
